Diagnosis . Th e very pronounced crest on the elytral base distinguishes this species from all others in Hispaniola . Additionally, the setae on the tubercles are partially erect, appearing as small tufts. The arrangement of black maculae on the pronotum is also distinctive (although somewhat similar to
L. argentatus
) as is the combination of very highly elevated anterolateral pronotal tubercles, dark integument, and very elongate ventrite 5 in females.
